"Mörner N.-A.","Estimating future sea level changes from past records",2004,"Global and Planetary Change","40","1-2",,"49","54",,,10.1016/S0921-8181(03)00097-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0346012637&partnerID=40&md5=3e849daf30702600284affb5bb1fc3c3","Paleogeophysics and Geodynamics, Stockholm University, S-10691 Stockholm, Sweden","Mörner, N.-A., Paleogeophysics and Geodynamics, Stockholm University, S-10691 Stockholm, Sweden","In the last 5000 years, global mean sea level has been dominated by the redistribution of water masses over the globe. In the last 300 years, sea level has been oscillation close to the present with peak rates in the period 1890-1930. Between 1930 and 1950, sea fell. The late 20th century lack any sign of acceleration. Satellite altimetry indicates virtually no changes in the last decade. Therefore, observationally based predictions of future sea level in the year 2100 will give a value of + 10 ± 10 cm (or + 5 ± 15 cm), by this discarding model outputs by IPCC as well as global loading models. This implies that there is no fear of any massive future flooding as claimed in most global warming scenarios. © 2003 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Future predictions; Models versus observations; Past records; Sea level changes","numerical model; paleoceanography; prediction; sea level change",,,,,,"Fairbridge, R.W., Krebs, O.A., Sea level and the southern oscillation (1962) Geophys. J., 6, pp. 532-545; Grossman, E.E., Fletcher, C.H., Richmond, B.M., The Holocene sea-level highstand in the equatorial Pacific: Analysis of the insular paleosea-level database (1998) Coral Reefs, 17, pp. 309-327; Gutenberg, B., Changes in sea level, postglacial uplift and mobility of the Earth's interior (1941) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 52, pp. 721-772; Hoffman, J.S., Keyes, D., Titus, J.G., (1983) Projecting Future Sea Level Rise, 266p. , US Environmental Protection Agency. Gov. Print. Office, Washington, DC; (1992) Global Change, , Reducing Unce